<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="436" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,727,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Etymology.</emphasis>
The present name is derived from the Latin “ 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[900,958,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">brevi</emphasis>
”(short) and “ 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1124,1199,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">spinus</emphasis>
”(spine), it refers to theshort spines on reduced inner distal processes on original gonocoxites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="436" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,799,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">Remarks</emphasis>
: This new species clearly belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[763,894,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipennis">
<emphasis box="[763,894,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">longipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group by the following shared characters: apical 
<number box="[151,161,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[171,187,836,860]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" value="4.0">4</number>
of wings darkened, and a fusion of the epandrium and paraprocts. It is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Wiedemann" authorityName="Wiedemann" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipennis">
<emphasis box="[1271,1436,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">P. longipennis</emphasis>
Wiedemann
</taxonomicName>
by external morphological characters, but it can be distinguished by the wholly yellow pleura; the male terminalia, are very close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Rozkosny &amp; Kovac" authorityName="Rozkosny &amp; Kovac" box="[535,924,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longispinus">
<emphasis box="[535,692,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="436">P. longispinus</emphasis>
Rozkošný &amp; Kovac
</taxonomicName>
, but the inner distal processes of gonocoxites are considerably reduced and their inner spine-like projections are only minute (Fig, 
<number box="[1100,1116,943,968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="436" value="5.0">5</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
